'''Henry Naylor''' (born 19 January 1966){{citation needed|date=September 2016}} is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[comedy writer]], director and [[performer]].<ref name="times_head">{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article3666386.ece |publisher=The Times |date=5 April 2008 |title=ITV's satire show Headcases to be more than Spitting Images lookalike |accessdate=2008-05-05  | location=London | first=Bruce | last=Dessau}}</ref>

He was head writer for ''[[Spitting Image]]'',{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} and has written for many shows including, ''[[Alas Smith and Jones]]'', ''[[Dead Ringers (comedy)|Dead Ringers]]'' and ''[[Big Impression|Alistair McGowan's Big Impression]]''.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} His work helped these shows to win numerous awards, including the British Comedy Award, and The Sony Gold.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

With his comedy partner [[Andy Parsons]], he has performed satirical shows in live venues in [[Australia]] and as part of the [[Edinburgh Fringe]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} ''[[Parsons and Naylorâ€™s Pull-Out Sections]]'' broadcast its ninth season on [[BBC Radio 2]] during Spring 2007.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} A compilation CD was released in 2003.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} The duo also set up London's first comedy sketch club TBA, at the [[Gate Theatre]] in the 1990s, and in the process helped discover many of Britain's leading sketch performers including [[Armstrong and Miller]], [[Tony Gardner]] and [[The Cheese Shop]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

In 2008, he created, directed and acted as executive producer on ''[[Headcases]]'', a satirical ITV show very similar to ''Spitting Image'', but made with [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] rather than puppets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2007/05/17/5332/a_spitting_image_for_the_digital_age |title=A Spitting Image for the digital age : News 2007 : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide |publisher=Chortle |date=2007-05-17 |accessdate=2010-04-09}}</ref> The show won numerous prestigious TV awards - including the RTS for Design and Innovation, and the C21 Award for Best New Sketch Show at Cannes' Mipcom - and was nominated for Best New Programme in the Broadcast Awards.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

On the live circuit, Henry has been regular at the Edinburgh Festival, performing, writing and directing numerous sketch shows and plays (15 in total).{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} In 2014 he was awarded one of the Festival's highest accolades, the Fringe First. He was also one of the international acts invited to perform at the Melbourne and Sydney Comedy Festivals.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

He also played [[Rowan Atkinson]]'s sidekick 'Bough' in a series of 17 commercials for [[Barclaycard]].<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/henry-naylor-from-spitting-image-to-syria-xqlwr2s8j</ref>

In 2003 he was in the news for throwing a full [[English breakfast]] at [[David Blaine]] during his ''Above the Below'' stunt on the South Bank of the [[River Thames]] in [[London]].<ref>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/blaines-strange-friend-6954401.html%3Famp</ref>

==Plays==
Naylor has written and directed award-winning plays for the Edinburgh Fringe, usually playing in [[The Gilded Balloon]] Teviot. ''Finding Bin Laden'' (2003) was a satire about the media's representation of the [[2003 Invasion of Iraq]], which also featured co-producer Sam Maynard's documentary photography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturewars.org.uk/edinburgh2003/war/findingbinladen.htm|title=Finding Bin Laden|publisher=}}</ref>

''Hunting Diana'', his 2004 Fringe offering, was about conspiracy theories surrounding the death of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]].<ref>[http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/whatson.cfm?id=970512004 ''The Scotsman''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050125052805/http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/whatson.cfm?id=970512004 |date=25 January 2005 }} ''Hunting Diana'' review</ref>

In 2007 he directed [[Sarah Kendall]]'s Fringe show ''My Very First Kidnapping''.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

In the summer of 2014 he wrote his first drama-tragedy - ''The Collector'' - which won one of the leading awards at the Edinburgh Festival, the Fringe First.<ref>[http://www.wow247.co.uk/blog/2014/08/08/scotsman-fringe-first-awards-first-winners-of-2014-announced/]"Fringe First Winner" announcement</ref><ref>[http://www.wow247.co.uk/blog/2014/08/07/cuckooed-the-collector-sochi-2014-the-trial-of-jane-fonda/]"The Collector" review</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sgfringe.com/2014/08/10/sg2014-review-the-collector/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140923013235/http://sgfringe.com/2014/08/10/sg2014-review-the-collector/ |archivedate=23 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Set in an Iraqi gaol during the occupation of Iraq in 2003, the play attacked brutality on both sides of the conflict. The show transferred off-London's [[West End]], and played a sell-out season at the [[Arcola Theatre]] in November 2014, to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegizzlereview.com/2014/11/the-collector-arcola-theatre.html|title=The Collector @ The Arcola Theatre - THE GIZZLE REVIEW|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://gingerhibiscus.com/review-the-collector-at-the-arcola-theatre/][http://exeuntmagazine.com/reviews/the-collector/]</ref> In autumn of 2016, the show will be going on an extensive 3-month tour of the UK.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

In 2015, he premiered the second part of his ''Arabian Nightmares - Echoes''. Opening at the ''Gilded Balloon'', it won the Spirit of the Fringe Award at Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edfringe.com/media/award-winners#Mervyn|title=2015 Award Winners - Edinburgh Festival Fringe|publisher=}}</ref> Exploring the surprising parallels between the [[Jihad|Jihadi]] adventurers of today and early [[Victorian period|Victorian]] pioneers, the play was a provocative and brutal examination of [[colonialism]], and the resonances of history. ''Echoes'' received many highly favourable reviews, including one from the [[The Guardian|Guardianâ€™s]] lead critic [[Mark Lawson]], who described it as a â€˜hugely impressive play.â€™<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/aug/12/echoes-at-edinburgh-festival-review-henry-naylor-isis?CMP=share_btn_fb|title=Echoes at Edinburgh festival review â€“ dark and daring look at colonial cruelty|author=Mark Lawson|work=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/stage/edinburgh-festival/article4534345.ece|title=Echoes at the Gilded Balloon, Edinburgh Festival|work=The Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wow247.co.uk/2015/08/31/theatre-review-echoes-by-henry-naylor/|title=Theatre review: Echoes by Henry Naylor|date=31 August 2015|work=WOW247}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/scotland/edinburghfestival/article1593272.ece|title=Timely drama finds echoes of the past - The Sunday Times|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thequotidiantimes.wordpress.com/2015/08/24/echoes/|title=ECHOES|work=thequotidiantimes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fringereview.co.uk/review/edinburgh-fringe/2015/echoes/|title=Echoes|work=FringeReview}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwaybaby.com/shows/echoes-by-henry-naylor/706386|title=Echoes by Henry Naylor|date=9 August 2015|work=Broadway Baby}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edfestmag.com/echoes-2/|title=Echoes  Edinburgh, festival|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theatreextra.blogspot.co.uk/2015/08/echos.html|title=theatreextra: Echos|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsawardvoice.com/magazine/reviews/Echoes-Henry-Naylor|title=Echoes by Henry Naylor|work=Arts Award Voice}}</ref> The play transferred both off-West End and off-Broadway - to the Arcola Theatre in London (November 2015), and to the [[59e59 Theater]] in New York (April 2016).{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} Its world tour commenced in early 2016 - and at the world's second largest Fringe - [[Adelaide]] - the show became one of the most decorated at the festival's history, winning 5 major Fringe Awards, including for Best Theatre, Critics' Choice and Pick of the Fringe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adelaidefringe.com.au/news/2016-adelaide-fringe-award-winners|title=Adelaide Fringe - 12 February - 14 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adelaidefringe.com.au/news/2016-fringe-weekly-award-winners-1|title=Adelaide Fringe - 12 February - 14 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/The-Adelaide-Critics-Circle-523375624347011/|title=Security Check Required|publisher=}}</ref> Again, it scored stellar five-star reviews.<ref>[http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/entertainment/adelaide-fringe/theatre/adelaide-fringe-festival-review-2016-echoes-by-henry-naylor/news-story/9e9ab17ff8ff937dcbf70c16bf5e8372 No Cookies | The Advertiser<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theatreguide.com.au/current_site/reviews/reviews_detail.php?ShowID=echoes&ShowYear=2016|title=Adelaide Theatre Guide: South Australia's Comprehensive Internet Guide to Local Arts|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebarefootreview.com.au/menu/theatre/119-2014-adelaide-reviews/1273-echoes-by-henry-naylor.html|title=Echoes by Henry Naylor|author=Samela Harris|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainmenthive.com.au/review-echoes_by_henry_naylor.htm|title=review-echoes_by_henry_naylor|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamadelaide.com.au/main/fringe-review-echoes/|title=Fringe Review: Echoes|work=Glam Adelaide - The Best South Australian News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indaily.com.au/arts-and-culture/adelaide-fringe/2016/02/12/review-echoes/|title=Review: Echoes|work=InDaily}}</ref> In 2016 Naylor is due to premiere the third instalment of the Arabian Nightmares at the Gilded Balloon - its working title being 'Angel.'{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}

